00:26:25,952 --> 00:26:27,651
They're tremendously
beautiful windows

501
00:26:27,653 --> 00:26:30,921
and those were very iconic
gene Moore displays.

502
00:26:30,923 --> 00:26:33,057
Perhaps that was
the first time that people

503
00:26:33,059 --> 00:26:35,993
saw, on a global scale,
gene Moore's work.

504
00:26:55,381 --> 00:26:57,748
It's fun.
It's all part
of the whole thing.

505
00:26:57,750 --> 00:26:59,283
It's fun to do.

506
00:26:59,285 --> 00:27:04,054
I love doing it even,
uh, after all these years.

507
00:27:04,056 --> 00:27:07,157
Gene was really a pioneer
in modern window display.

508
00:27:07,159 --> 00:27:09,660
Because in the past,
the idea was

509
00:27:09,662 --> 00:27:12,696
cram as much as you could
into the window

510
00:27:12,698 --> 00:27:14,231
and have
all the price tags on it

511
00:27:14,233 --> 00:27:16,800
and it's all about
pushing the merchandise,

512
00:27:16,802 --> 00:27:18,869
but gene distilled it.

513
00:27:18,871 --> 00:27:20,738
He would show one
or two pieces,

514
00:27:20,740 --> 00:27:23,073
but it was the way you got in
was you wanted to see

515
00:27:23,075 --> 00:27:24,808
what he was gonna do
with the windows.

516
00:27:24,810 --> 00:27:26,410
People have forgotten,
the new generation

517
00:27:26,412 --> 00:27:28,012
doesn't really know.

518
00:27:28,014 --> 00:27:31,015
I don't think that they know
the whole story.

519
00:27:32,718 --> 00:27:35,986
I've been known to break
a glass in the window.

520
00:27:35,988 --> 00:27:41,191
And that was fun because
people would call up and say,

521
00:27:41,193 --> 00:27:43,427
"you know you have
a broken glass in the window?"

522
00:27:43,429 --> 00:27:47,798
I say, yes, I know.
There's the hammer right
beside it that broke it.

523
00:27:47,800 --> 00:27:52,036
I learned to do
things different--

524
00:27:52,038 --> 00:27:55,205
uh, to make a difference,
because

525
00:27:55,207 --> 00:27:58,242
I wanted to see how much
attention people paid to it.

526
00:27:58,244 --> 00:27:59,943
And they would
call up and say,

527
00:27:59,945 --> 00:28:02,112
"do you know you have
one knife turned backwards?

528
00:28:02,114 --> 00:28:04,848
Or one key
turned backwards?"

529
00:28:04,850 --> 00:28:06,216
I said, "yeah."

530
00:28:06,218 --> 00:28:08,452
And then I knew that
people looked at it.

531
00:28:08,454 --> 00:28:10,154
It's the only way
i could check up.

532
00:28:20,932 --> 00:28:26,437
Gene Moore had a wonderful
sense of wit in place.

533
00:28:26,439 --> 00:28:30,174
He understood the whole theatre
of window design.

534
00:28:30,176 --> 00:28:32,810
He took it to a place
that would use

535
00:28:32,812 --> 00:28:36,980
incongruous objects
with beautiful jewelry.

536
00:28:54,466 --> 00:28:56,934
I would walk around
the floor with gene,

537
00:28:56,936 --> 00:29:00,003
you know, selecting product
for the window.

538
00:29:00,005 --> 00:29:02,072
He used to love to use eggs.

539
00:29:02,074 --> 00:29:03,941
You know,
he used to blowout eggs

540
00:29:03,943 --> 00:29:05,976
and use eggs
a different way.

541
00:29:05,978 --> 00:29:07,444
Eggs, to me,

542
00:29:07,446 --> 00:29:09,913
is the most perfect shape
in the whole world.

543
00:29:09,915 --> 00:29:11,915
I like 'em the way
they come right out of the hen.

544
00:29:11,917 --> 00:29:13,751
I don't believe in
painted eggs.

545
00:29:13,753 --> 00:29:15,452
Eggs are not to be painted.

546
00:29:15,454 --> 00:29:17,955
They are so beautiful
in themselves

547
00:29:17,957 --> 00:29:20,257
that I'd leave them
the way they are.

548
00:29:20,259 --> 00:29:24,795
It was always sort
of juxtaposed jewelry
and something unique.

549
00:29:24,797 --> 00:29:26,797
He just did
whatever he wanted.

550
00:29:26,799 --> 00:29:29,166
The labor that went into
creating those things

551
00:29:29,168 --> 00:29:30,868
and the artists he engaged

552
00:29:30,870 --> 00:29:33,370
because he did engage people
to work with him.

553
00:29:33,372 --> 00:29:35,205
And they were on
his rolodex.

554
00:29:35,207 --> 00:29:37,341
They were not on
anyone else's rolodex.

555
00:29:37,343 --> 00:29:39,209
You were nev-- and they were
very true to him.

556
00:29:39,211 --> 00:29:41,478
One of his most
spectacular windows

557
00:29:41,480 --> 00:29:44,882
was a giant white sphere

558
00:29:44,884 --> 00:29:47,217
hanging over
a strand of pearls.

559
00:29:47,219 --> 00:29:49,286
And I'd put them in
and I thought,

560
00:29:49,288 --> 00:29:51,822
something is wrong.

561
00:29:51,824 --> 00:29:54,158
You know, it's-- it's too clean.

562
00:29:54,160 --> 00:29:56,026
It's wrong.

563
00:29:56,028 --> 00:29:59,029
So, I broke a string of Pearl--
i thought I'll catch hell,

564
00:29:59,031 --> 00:30:00,397
but I broke a string
of pearls

565
00:30:00,399 --> 00:30:02,833
and I had the pearls,
you know...

566
00:30:02,835 --> 00:30:04,168
And it helped the window.

567
00:30:04,170 --> 00:30:06,370
It made the window
as a matter of fact.

568
00:30:06,372 --> 00:30:08,405
And only gene
would have been able

569
00:30:08,407 --> 00:30:10,908
to get away with showing
damaged goods

570
00:30:10,910 --> 00:30:12,976
in the windows at Tiffany's.

571
00:30:12,978 --> 00:30:15,846
They the--teasing glimpse

572
00:30:15,848 --> 00:30:20,150
into a world
that you want to be part of.

573
00:30:20,152 --> 00:30:22,052
It was very humbling
to be thinking

574
00:30:22,054 --> 00:30:24,822
I'm part of something
that's ended up

575
00:30:24,824 --> 00:30:28,025
in a window at Tiffany's
on fifth Avenue.

576
00:30:28,027 --> 00:30:29,459
I mean,
it's a privilege and a joy.

577
00:30:29,461 --> 00:30:32,095
Imagine a house
of Tiffany's saying,

578
00:30:32,097 --> 00:30:35,199
hey, go and make
anything you want,

579
00:30:35,201 --> 00:30:40,204
and work with these
extraordinary crafts people
upstairs

580
00:30:40,206 --> 00:30:44,441
who literally still
hand make the items.

581
00:30:44,443 --> 00:30:47,878
Is that you, my lovely?

582
00:30:51,216 --> 00:30:55,185
Daisy Buchanan,
"the golden girl."

583
00:30:55,187 --> 00:30:57,387
A breathless warmth
flowed from her.

584
00:30:57,389 --> 00:31:00,324
A promise that there was
no one else in the world

585
00:31:00,326 --> 00:31:02,159
she so wanted to see.

586
00:31:02,161 --> 00:31:04,328
Do they miss me in Chicago?

587
00:31:04,330 --> 00:31:08,298
Uh, yes. Um--um,
at least a dozen people
send their love.

588
00:31:08,300 --> 00:31:10,200
How gorgeous.

589
00:31:10,202 --> 00:31:11,969
I've just been in China.

590
00:31:11,971 --> 00:31:14,905
I've just released
"the great gatsby" in China.

591
00:31:14,907 --> 00:31:17,207
Yes, they're dazzled
by all the luxury.

592
00:31:17,209 --> 00:31:21,478
But they're also very aware
of the heart issue of the book.

593
00:31:21,480 --> 00:31:25,916
And that is this paradox
between this roaring '20s,

594
00:31:25,918 --> 00:31:29,887
where there's "such an orgy of
money," to quote Fitzgerald.

595
00:31:29,889 --> 00:31:32,990
And then there's
this kind of devastation

596
00:31:32,992 --> 00:31:36,293
in the American dream,
if you like.

597
00:31:36,295 --> 00:31:38,662
There must be a center
and there must be meaning.

598
00:31:38,664 --> 00:31:41,965
In the last ten years,

599
00:31:41,967 --> 00:31:44,067
the people
have just experienced

600
00:31:44,069 --> 00:31:45,402
a tremendous change.

601
00:31:45,404 --> 00:31:47,537
Not just in their lifestyle,
but in the--

602
00:31:47,539 --> 00:31:50,340
in the way they feel
about themselves.

603
00:31:50,342 --> 00:31:53,277
A lot of Chinese
were starting to get wealthy

604
00:31:53,279 --> 00:31:55,078
and they thought
with that wealth

605
00:31:55,080 --> 00:31:57,915
they should treat themselves
a little bit better.

606
00:31:57,917 --> 00:31:59,416
And they've got
to this point now

607
00:31:59,418 --> 00:32:02,953
where, finally, they can
live a beautiful life

608
00:32:02,955 --> 00:32:06,990
and they can start thinking
about what they really want

609
00:32:06,992 --> 00:32:08,659
and not just
what they need.

610
00:32:08,661 --> 00:32:11,061
This idea
of the American dream and--

611
00:32:11,063 --> 00:32:14,231
and when you think
"American dream,
"Chinese dream,"

612
00:32:14,233 --> 00:32:16,967
and the vision
that they both speak to,

613
00:32:16,969 --> 00:32:19,503
you realize
that all the values

614
00:32:19,505 --> 00:32:22,572
that they're selling
are universal.

615
00:32:22,574 --> 00:32:25,008
I don't even want to own
anything till I can find a place

616
00:32:25,010 --> 00:32:26,677
where a million things
go together.

617
00:32:26,679 --> 00:32:29,046
I'm not sure
where that is, but--

618
00:32:29,048 --> 00:32:32,482
--i know what it's like.

619
00:32:32,484 --> 00:32:35,352
-It's like Tiffany's.
-Tiffany's?

620
00:32:35,354 --> 00:32:38,588
-You mean the jewelry store?
-That's right.

621
00:32:38,590 --> 00:32:40,991
I'm crazy
about Tiffany's.

622
00:32:40,993 --> 00:32:44,227
Although Tiffany in its-- its
current incarnation

623
00:32:44,229 --> 00:32:47,030
is not
a celebrity-driven brand,

624
00:32:47,032 --> 00:32:51,068
the one celebrity
who is beyond reproach,
who is enduringly popular,

625
00:32:51,070 --> 00:32:52,436
who will always
be associated

626
00:32:52,438 --> 00:32:54,071
with the brand
is Audrey hepburn.

627
00:32:54,073 --> 00:32:56,573
I was definitely
familiarized with--

628
00:32:56,575 --> 00:32:58,542
with the whole notion
of Tiffany's

629
00:32:58,544 --> 00:33:00,744
through the movie
"breakfast at Tiffany's."

630
00:33:00,746 --> 00:33:03,347
For me when I was younger
seeing that movie,

631
00:33:03,349 --> 00:33:06,616
seeing her and seeing
the name "Tiffany's,"

632
00:33:06,618 --> 00:33:09,753
embodied everything
that was glamorous,

633
00:33:09,755 --> 00:33:12,723
and slightly unattainable,
about New York.

634
00:33:12,725 --> 00:33:14,424
Well, no, because
of the title,

635
00:33:14,426 --> 00:33:15,726
great product placement

636
00:33:15,728 --> 00:33:17,594
without needing-- without
meaning it.

637
00:33:17,596 --> 00:33:21,264
Tiffany got lucky,
sort of in the same way that

638
00:33:21,266 --> 00:33:23,734
Campbell's soup got lucky
with Andy warhol.

639
00:33:23,736 --> 00:33:26,503
It just happened
that this film was made.

640
00:33:26,505 --> 00:33:29,673
It was not made for any kind
of advertorial purpose.

641
00:33:29,675 --> 00:33:32,175
It's perfect.
It's a perfect image.

642
00:33:32,177 --> 00:33:35,312
A lot of people confuse me
with Audrey hepburn. Um...

643
00:33:35,314 --> 00:33:37,381
There are good things about it,
there are horrible things
about it.

644
00:33:37,383 --> 00:33:39,016
- What's horrible?
-Mickey Rooney.

645
00:33:39,018 --> 00:33:42,386
--Ugh! Ooh!

646
00:33:42,388 --> 00:33:44,321
Mickey Rooney,
"breakfast at Tiffany's"?

647
00:33:44,323 --> 00:33:47,224
Where's his Oscar?
Come on!

648
00:33:47,226 --> 00:33:50,160
In 30 seconds
i got to call the police!

649
00:33:50,162 --> 00:33:52,029
That's grotesque.
And, of course,

650
00:33:52,031 --> 00:33:54,231
it was never actually "okay."
It was just allowed.

651
00:33:54,233 --> 00:33:55,766
You know, all kinds of things
were allowed,

652
00:33:55,768 --> 00:33:57,034
doesn't mean they're okay.

653
00:33:57,036 --> 00:33:58,802
I genuinely admire the movie.

654
00:33:58,804 --> 00:34:01,705
I admire the risks
that were taken

655
00:34:01,707 --> 00:34:03,807
by Audrey hepburn,
by Blake Edwards.

656
00:34:03,809 --> 00:34:07,044
Mancini and, uh, givenchy.

657
00:34:12,617 --> 00:34:14,384
You want a character
you're gonna love.

658
00:34:14,386 --> 00:34:16,420
Well, at the time,
i--i--

659
00:34:16,422 --> 00:34:18,422
I thought it was a very
interesting choice.

660
00:34:18,424 --> 00:34:21,558
I mean, she had style.
She had class.

661
00:34:21,560 --> 00:34:24,528
She had a quality, I think,
that--that worked.

662
00:34:24,530 --> 00:34:27,431
I don't think people know
that she was sort of like, uh,

663
00:34:27,433 --> 00:34:30,834
a prostitute-- high end kinda
prostitute in New York City,

664
00:34:30,836 --> 00:34:33,303
trying to claw her way
up to the top.

665
00:34:33,305 --> 00:34:37,274
I think when now they see it,
she looks like a socialite.

666
00:34:37,276 --> 00:34:38,408
They think she is a socialite.

667
00:34:48,119 --> 00:34:49,619
Won't you join me?

668
00:34:49,621 --> 00:34:51,621
Yes, join Audrey hepburn

669
00:34:51,623 --> 00:34:53,290
as you've never
seen her before--

670
00:34:53,292 --> 00:34:55,358
kicking over the traces
and bringing to life

671
00:34:55,360 --> 00:34:58,161
Truman capote's
"breakfast at Tiffany's."

672
00:35:00,165 --> 00:35:01,865
Well, the first time I saw
"breakfast at Tiffany's,"

673
00:35:01,867 --> 00:35:03,300
it didn't-- didn't cross my mind

674
00:35:03,302 --> 00:35:05,268
that she was a prostitute.

675
00:35:05,270 --> 00:35:08,305
Capote doesn't come
right out and say it,

676
00:35:08,307 --> 00:35:11,141
but if you read
between the lines

677
00:35:11,143 --> 00:35:14,778
it's something that
he wanted you to consider.

678
00:35:14,780 --> 00:35:17,481
My mom told me afterwards,
and I was like, "what?"

679
00:35:17,483 --> 00:35:19,649
Really? What'd she say?
She was like, "by the way--"

680
00:35:19,651 --> 00:35:22,119
yeah, she was like,
"you know that she's
a call-girl?"

681
00:35:22,121 --> 00:35:25,489
And I'm like, "wh--why?"

682
00:35:25,491 --> 00:35:27,824
"What gave you that sense?"

683
00:35:27,826 --> 00:35:29,826
But, yeah, I mean,
in retrospect,

684
00:35:29,828 --> 00:35:32,262
I'm like, "okay,
it's a bit obvious

685
00:35:32,264 --> 00:35:33,864
once you have that
in your mind."

686
00:35:33,866 --> 00:35:35,866
- She's a hooker?
- -Are you surprised

687
00:35:35,868 --> 00:35:37,400
they would make a doll
out of a hooker?

688
00:35:37,402 --> 00:35:38,902
Why'd they do that?

689
00:35:38,904 --> 00:35:41,238
- Seriously? She's a hooker?
- -Yeah.

690
00:35:41,240 --> 00:35:42,539
Then why is she
dressed like that

691
00:35:42,541 --> 00:35:44,541
going to Tiffany's
for breakfast?

692
00:35:44,543 --> 00:35:47,844
Think about what
you're seeing on screen.

693
00:35:47,846 --> 00:35:50,814
The sun is coming up...

694
00:35:50,816 --> 00:35:54,518
A beautiful girl,
in evening dress,

695
00:35:54,520 --> 00:35:56,853
is getting out of cab.

696
00:35:56,855 --> 00:35:58,889
Why? What is she doing

697
00:35:58,891 --> 00:36:01,591
in an evening dress
at that hour?

698
00:36:01,593 --> 00:36:04,327
Is she going out
to a party at sunrise?

699
00:36:04,329 --> 00:36:06,696
Probably not. More likely,

700
00:36:06,698 --> 00:36:09,799
she's coming home
from a party at sunrise.

701
00:36:09,801 --> 00:36:11,701
-And then the next--
-this is not a good examp--

702
00:36:11,703 --> 00:36:15,372
-and the next morning...
-Oh! So she... oh!

703
00:36:15,374 --> 00:36:17,307
So she hooked up
with a rich guy,

704
00:36:17,309 --> 00:36:19,709
-and she wants that guy--
-no. Well, not exactly.

705
00:36:19,711 --> 00:36:21,211
Then what's up
with her outfit?

706
00:36:21,213 --> 00:36:23,380
She wants extra cash
on the side,

707
00:36:23,382 --> 00:36:25,382
so she's always
hooking up with men, right?

708
00:36:25,384 --> 00:36:26,750
Well, yeah, I mean--

709
00:36:26,752 --> 00:36:28,885
she was... a gal

710
00:36:28,887 --> 00:36:31,788
who did take money
for entertaining guys,

711
00:36:31,790 --> 00:36:33,790
it didn't--it didn't
specifically say

712
00:36:33,792 --> 00:36:37,794
it became a sexual
situation or not. But, uh...

713
00:36:37,796 --> 00:36:40,564
I don't think,
in the film,

714
00:36:40,566 --> 00:36:42,365
you look at her as
an out-and-out hooker.

715
00:36:43,734 --> 00:36:45,502
She's got too many
other elements.

716
00:36:45,504 --> 00:36:47,571
You love her kookiness.

717
00:36:47,573 --> 00:36:49,773
"Kook" was one of the words--
it was kind of a code word.

718
00:36:49,775 --> 00:36:51,908
It was a-- it was a euphemism

719
00:36:51,910 --> 00:36:55,245
to, um, comfort
nervous audiences

720
00:36:55,247 --> 00:36:59,449
who knew a little bit about
what capote's novel was about,

721
00:36:59,451 --> 00:37:01,685
and get them to feel,
sort of, more comfortable

722
00:37:01,687 --> 00:37:03,987
with the idea that
they were seeing

723
00:37:03,989 --> 00:37:06,556
a friendly movie,
a safe movie.

724
00:37:06,558 --> 00:37:09,993
It may not have been
capote's original concept,

725
00:37:09,995 --> 00:37:12,495
then I guess that
was a studio decision

726
00:37:12,497 --> 00:37:16,233
for what they wanted
Holly golightly to be like.

727
00:37:16,235 --> 00:37:18,702
Marilyn is closer

728
00:37:18,704 --> 00:37:20,937
to the Holly golightly
in the novel.

729
00:37:20,939 --> 00:37:22,872
So, on a certain level,

730
00:37:22,874 --> 00:37:27,377
it makes sense that Truman
would want her.

731
00:37:27,379 --> 00:37:29,613
Man, you guys-- you guys
are lucky that we just woke up.

732
00:37:29,615 --> 00:37:32,616
-We're really raw
-yeah, we're really raw.

733
00:37:33,784 --> 00:37:35,452
Can we--can we talk about

734
00:37:35,454 --> 00:37:36,753
the song,
"breakfast at Tiffany's"?

735
00:37:36,755 --> 00:37:38,388
Sure, go ahead.

736
00:37:38,390 --> 00:37:40,790
But we were out in montauk
a couple years ago,

737
00:37:40,792 --> 00:37:43,426
we were deejaying
our friend's wedding,

738
00:37:43,428 --> 00:37:45,795
and we found ourselves
on the beach

739
00:37:45,797 --> 00:37:48,632
trying to start
a bonfire.

740
00:37:48,634 --> 00:37:51,301
And, uh...
Before we knew it,

741
00:37:51,303 --> 00:37:54,304
we were joined by a bunch
of Ukrainian or...

742
00:37:54,306 --> 00:37:56,640
-Eastern European, Ukrainian
