1029
00:51:21,112 --> 00:51:22,211
What does it say?

1030
00:51:22,213 --> 00:51:23,579
It says, "i don't know you."

1031
00:51:32,255 --> 00:51:34,290
"Someone will move away,

1032
00:51:34,292 --> 00:51:35,825
someone will come home,

1033
00:51:35,827 --> 00:51:38,494
someone will
finally graduate..."

1034
00:51:43,467 --> 00:51:45,301
What we're doing
when we do this

1035
00:51:45,303 --> 00:51:48,871
is to explain Tiffany's
purpose in the world

1036
00:51:48,873 --> 00:51:51,107
to, maybe,
a younger generation

1037
00:51:51,109 --> 00:51:52,575
that is not familiar with it.

1038
00:51:52,577 --> 00:51:54,477
It's a little lost
on my generation

1039
00:51:54,479 --> 00:51:57,513
'cause I think
it's a bit... tired.

1040
00:51:57,515 --> 00:52:01,617
And there's a lot
of psychological components
to Tiffany's.

1041
00:52:01,619 --> 00:52:03,319
We touch on
the products we sell,

1042
00:52:03,321 --> 00:52:07,723
like engagement rings
and gifts for special occasions,

1043
00:52:07,725 --> 00:52:09,725
but there's
no direct selling here.

1044
00:52:09,727 --> 00:52:11,393
It's just an attitude.

1045
00:52:11,395 --> 00:52:14,730
It's a feeling
about our customer,

1046
00:52:14,732 --> 00:52:16,632
and who we are.

1047
00:52:16,634 --> 00:52:18,634
I think it is
a little bit of a brainwash.

1048
00:52:18,636 --> 00:52:22,771
A lot of the ads
are white families.

1049
00:52:22,773 --> 00:52:26,876
It's--it's a little bit
of a 1950s kind of feel to it.

1050
00:52:26,878 --> 00:52:29,578
We want to speak
to our customer

1051
00:52:29,580 --> 00:52:32,848
as a human being,
as someone who has a family.

1052
00:52:32,850 --> 00:52:35,351
Maybe have children,
maybe wants to get married.

1053
00:52:35,353 --> 00:52:38,621
It stretches true love
so much,

1054
00:52:38,623 --> 00:52:40,689
it's such an unrealistic
true love.

1055
00:52:40,691 --> 00:52:43,192
Which also, I think,
gives us

1056
00:52:43,194 --> 00:52:44,860
a little bit
of a "yuck."

1057
00:53:46,756 --> 00:53:48,757
I was about 11 years old

1058
00:53:48,759 --> 00:53:50,993
and I saw the ad
in the "New York times,"

1059
00:53:50,995 --> 00:53:52,494
where Tiffany's ads
have always been,

1060
00:53:52,496 --> 00:53:53,996
I saw an ad for a ring.

1061
00:53:53,998 --> 00:53:57,666
And the ring was--
cost $176,000.

1062
00:53:57,668 --> 00:53:59,001
I remember thinking
that was just

1063
00:53:59,003 --> 00:54:00,936
an inconceivable amount
of money.

1064
00:54:00,938 --> 00:54:02,871
I was the son
of two writers,

1065
00:54:02,873 --> 00:54:05,307
we were not rich by any stretch
of the imagination,

1066
00:54:05,309 --> 00:54:06,809
and that just
seemed incredible.

1067
00:54:06,811 --> 00:54:09,445
And so I wrote this letter.
And, on the one hand,

1068
00:54:09,447 --> 00:54:11,280
it was... I could
do the math, and so

1069
00:54:11,282 --> 00:54:13,482
it was a slightly
snarky letter, I suppose,

1070
00:54:13,484 --> 00:54:14,817
but at the same time
i was 11 years old.

1071
00:54:14,819 --> 00:54:17,386
I remember thinking,
"well, you never know."

1072
00:54:17,388 --> 00:54:18,420
"Dear Tiffany's...

1073
00:54:30,467 --> 00:54:32,635
"Sincerely, David joblanski."

1074
00:54:34,471 --> 00:54:35,537
"Dear David..."

1075
00:54:55,058 --> 00:54:57,393
Well, there's one man
who agrees with that.

1076
00:54:57,395 --> 00:54:58,727
His name
is Walter hoving

1077
00:54:58,729 --> 00:55:01,497
and he is the president,
chief executive officer

1078
00:55:01,499 --> 00:55:03,832
of Tiffany, a store
of which you may have heard.

1079
00:55:03,834 --> 00:55:05,768
-And here's tom brokaw.
-Thank you, gene.

1080
00:55:05,770 --> 00:55:07,770
Walter hoving has been
in retailing

1081
00:55:07,772 --> 00:55:09,772
for 60 years now,
and he has been affiliated

1082
00:55:09,774 --> 00:55:11,940
with places as different
as Montgomery ward's

1083
00:55:11,942 --> 00:55:14,343
and bonwitt and teller
and lord and Taylor.

1084
00:55:14,345 --> 00:55:16,912
And for the past 23 years,
he's been the chairman
of Tiffany's.

1085
00:55:16,914 --> 00:55:18,547
Last week he placed an ad

1086
00:55:18,549 --> 00:55:20,349
in a newspaper, it said...

1087
00:55:26,022 --> 00:55:28,457
Mr. hoving, why aren't you
open on Sundays?

1088
00:55:28,459 --> 00:55:30,592
After all, this is
the biggest time of the year,
i would suspect,

1089
00:55:30,594 --> 00:55:32,861
-for Tiffany's.
-We think our customers
need a rest.

1090
00:55:32,863 --> 00:55:35,364
So we keep closed
on Sundays.

1091
00:55:35,366 --> 00:55:37,866
Mr. hoving, you have
on sale at Tiffany's

1092
00:55:37,868 --> 00:55:40,869
an emerald necklace
that is worth $1,700,000

1093
00:55:40,871 --> 00:55:43,706
and you have a diamond
that is worth $7 million,

1094
00:55:43,708 --> 00:55:45,040
- I think, all together.
-That's right.

1095
00:55:45,042 --> 00:55:46,875
What if someone
were passing through town,

1096
00:55:46,877 --> 00:55:49,745
and decided that they wanted
to buy one of those two items,

1097
00:55:49,747 --> 00:55:51,547
but they were only
available on Sunday.

1098
00:55:51,549 --> 00:55:53,716
Would you open the store to sell
them one of those two items?

1099
00:55:53,718 --> 00:55:56,885
- No, we would not. No.
-You'd pass
on that sale?

1100
00:55:56,887 --> 00:55:58,721
- That's right.
- -Walter hoving,

1101
00:55:58,723 --> 00:56:00,556
outspoken chairman
of the board
of a little store,

1102
00:56:00,558 --> 00:56:02,124
as we like to say on
the corner here in New York,

1103
00:56:02,126 --> 00:56:03,592
called Tiffany's.

1104
00:56:28,718 --> 00:56:30,586
Is it heavy
when you pick it up?

1105
00:56:30,588 --> 00:56:32,588
Uh, not really, no.
