00:58:20,196 --> 00:58:24,032
George steinbrenner bought
the Yankees in 1973.

1125
00:58:24,034 --> 00:58:27,703
At that time, I think
the top hat logo
was more in use.

1126
00:58:27,705 --> 00:58:30,038
It adorned
every team publication,

1127
00:58:30,040 --> 00:58:31,874
it was more commonly used.

1128
00:58:31,876 --> 00:58:35,143
He was more attracted
to the interlocking "n-y."

1129
00:58:35,145 --> 00:58:37,546
He thought there was something
very classy about it.

1130
00:58:37,548 --> 00:58:40,048
So, almost immediately from
the time he owned the team,

1131
00:58:40,050 --> 00:58:42,150
that was the logo of choice.

1132
00:58:42,152 --> 00:58:45,721
Tiffany had designed
that interlocking "n-y"

1133
00:58:45,723 --> 00:58:49,291
on a police medal
that was given in 1877

1134
00:58:49,293 --> 00:58:52,227
to a wounded New York City
police officer.

1135
00:58:52,229 --> 00:58:54,062
One of the Yankees'
two owners

1136
00:58:54,064 --> 00:58:56,732
in their first decade
of existence

1137
00:58:56,734 --> 00:58:58,567
was William devery,

1138
00:58:58,569 --> 00:59:01,937
who had been chief of police
of New York City.

1139
00:59:01,939 --> 00:59:06,041
William devery probably kept
that "n-y" design

1140
00:59:06,043 --> 00:59:08,744
in some form
of circulation

1141
00:59:08,746 --> 00:59:11,914
and he was still half-owner
of the team in 1909

1142
00:59:11,916 --> 00:59:14,016
when it first appeared
on the yankee uniform.

